node.text:
The number of dead and missing in this weekend's catastrophic Tennessee flooding was revised Tuesday after further investigation by local officials. The death toll now sits at 18, with three unaccounted for.

“Our current count has come down because of a mistake in the way we were tallying our missing and deceased," Waverly Police Chief Grant Gillespie said in a Tuesday afternoon news conference.

On Monday, officials had said 22 were dead and dozens still missing.

In Tuesday's announcement, Gillespie said the death toll was revised after it was discovered there had been some confusion during the chaotic and quick-moving response effort on Saturday morning.

“It's still a tremendous loss of life," Gillespie said. "I hope that number doesn’t grow.”

Tap the link in our bio to read more.

📷: Nashville Fire Department via Getty Images

node.text:
More than 15 inches of rain fell in 24 hours on parts of Tennessee on Saturday, Aug. 21. The flash floods that followed killed at least 22 people. 

Extreme rainfall events like this one are happening more often, and climate change is a huge factor. 

Tap the link in our bio to learn how. 

📸: Brett Carlsen / Getty Images

Structures and vehicles are piled up against a bridge over Trace Creek in Waverly, Tennessee, on Aug. 23, 2021. 

#ClimateChange #rain #Tennessee #FlashFlood

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Weather Channel in Greenland. May be an image of mountain and text that says 'Rain Falls on Greenland Ice Cap Peak for First Time in Recorded History'.

node.text:
It rained on Greenland's ice cap peak for the first time in recorded history on Aug. 14, 2021.

But scientists had no way of measuring it since rain isn't the type of weather they expect to see there.

The rain fell during a three-day heat wave, and it wasn't the only heat wave to hit the country this summer.

Heat waves can trigger major melting events in Greenland that scientists say will become more common in the future.

Tap the link in our bio to learn more.

📸 : Cavan Images/Getty Images
#ClimateChange #Greenland #melting #rain

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by The Weather Channel on August 23, 2021. May be an image of fire, outdoors and text that says 'California's Explosive Wildfires Could Burn Until December'.

node.text:
The news keeps getting worse for drought-plagued California.

The explosive wildfires that are burning through the state might not be extinguished until December due to the dry conditions and little relief expected in the coming months.

More than a dozen large fires are burning statewide, and in terms of acres burned, 2021 is pacing ahead of the record 2020 season.

And the warmer, drier conditions that have been intensified by climate change are leading to a year-round fire season in the West.

Tap the link in our bio for the full story.

📸: In this long exposure photo, flames from the Dixie Fire spread in Genesee, California, on Saturday, Aug. 21, 2021. (AP Photo/Ethan Swope)

#California #wildfire #DixieFire #ClimateChange

node.text:
Satellite imagery over several days captured a fascinating evolution – watch as Hurricane Grace makes landfall in Mexico as a Category 3 major hurricane early Saturday.

Then, watch it fall apart over Mexico Saturday and Sunday.

Then, watch it re-emerge in the Eastern Pacific and reform as Tropical Storm Marty.

A tropical system can undergo a name change if it dissipates over land and then reforms in a new basin. When that happens, it gets the next unused name in that basin's list. In this instance, that name in the Eastern Pacific was Marty.

Has your name ever been used as a tropical storm or hurricane name? Let us know in the comments below.

🎥: @noaa, hat tip to @jake.carstens

node.text:
One of the worst flooding disasters on record in Middle Tennessee worsened on Sunday with the announcement that at least 22 people had been killed, and dozens more remained missing.

Twelve additional deaths were reported by the sheriff in Humphreys County on Sunday, adding to the 10 confirmed Saturday night. The number of missing is now estimated at 50.

The hardest-hit area is about 40 miles west of Nashville.

Between 15 and 17 inches of rain was reported in 24 hours in areas around Dickson, Houston, Humphreys and Hickman counties.

And, if confirmed, a preliminary 24-hour rainfall total of 17.02 inches recorded in McEwen, Tennessee, would be a new state record and would break the old record by more than 3 inches.

Tap the link in our bio for the complete report on this deadly disaster.

📸: A car is among the debris that washed up against a bridge over a stream Sunday, Aug. 22, 2021, in Waverly, Tennessee. (AP Photo/Mark Humphrey)

A submerged vehicle is photographed following a flash flood in Helmetta, New Jersey, after Tropical Storm Henri passed the area on Aug. 22, 2021. Residents were being evacuated from the town on Sunday. 

Henri slammed into Rhode Island on the U.S. East Coast Sunday, knocking out power to thousands of Americans, canceling scores of flights and bringing record rainfall. The storm, earlier downgraded from a Category 1 hurricane, hit the town of Westerly, Rhode Island, at approximately 12:15 p.m. 

Click the link in our bio to see more photos of the storm.
